sratoolkit and STAR to align reads

First of all, to use sratoolkit I downloaded it to my folder on Amarel cluster.

curl --output sratoolkit.tar.gz https://ftp-trace.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/sra/sdk/current/sratoolkit.current-ubuntu64.tar.gz
tar -xzvf sratoolkit.tar.gz

Also, I downloaded human genome Homo_sapiens.GRCh38.dna.primary_assembly.fa.gz to index it later.

# Download *fa human genome
curl -O ftp://ftp.ensembl.org/pub/release-101/fasta/homo_sapiens/dna/Homo_sapiens.GRCh38.dna.primary_assembly.fa.gz
gunzip Homo_sapiens.GRCh38.dna.primary_assembly.fa.gz

# Download *gtf human genome
curl -O Homo_sapiens.GRCh38.101.gtf
gunzip Homo_sapiens.GRCh38.101.gtf

Then, I wrote a bash script index_genome.sh to index genome and run it with sbatch.

#!/bin/bash

#SBATCH --partition=p_amitrofa_1             # Partition (job queue)
#SBATCH --requeue                    # Return job to the queue if preempted
#SBATCH --job-name=STAR_index          # Assign an short name to your job
#SBATCH --nodes=1                    # Number of nodes you require
#SBATCH --ntasks=1                   # Total # of tasks across all nodes
#SBATCH --cpus-per-task=4           # Cores per task (>1 if multithread tasks)
#SBATCH --mem=124000                 # Real memory (RAM) required (MB)
#SBATCH --time=100:00:00              # Total run time limit (HH:MM:SS)
#SBATCH --output=slurm.%N.%j.out     # STDOUT output file
#SBATCH --error=slurm.%N.%j.err      # STDERR output file (optional)

module load STAR

STAR --runThreadN 4 \
--runMode genomeGenerate \
--genomeDir genome/ \
--genomeFastaFiles genome/Homo_sapiens.GRCh38.dna.primary_assembly.fa \
--sjdbGTFfile genome/Homo_sapiens.GRCh38.101.gtf \
--sjdbOverhang 50 # reads length 51-1=50

To align reads I wrote below script main_script.sh and run it. Firstly, I run it in my home directory on Amarel, however there is not enough space even I remove fastq file after each aligning. That is why other part of SRR files was run on labs resources.

LOG outputs in tarball are

  1. slurm.hal0271.37075165.err and slurm.hal0271.37075165.out
  2. slurm.hal0342.37098906.err and slurm.hal0342.37098906.out
#!/bin/bash

#SBATCH --partition=p_amitrofa_1             # Partition (job queue)
#SBATCH --requeue                    # Return job to the queue if preempted
#SBATCH --job-name=STAR          # Assign an short name to your job
#SBATCH --nodes=1                    # Number of nodes you require
#SBATCH --ntasks=1                   # Total # of tasks across all nodes
#SBATCH --cpus-per-task=4           # Cores per task (>1 if multithread tasks)
#SBATCH --mem=200000                 # Real memory (RAM) required (MB)
#SBATCH --time=100:00:00              # Total run time limit (HH:MM:SS)
#SBATCH --output=slurm.%N.%j.out     # STDOUT output file
#SBATCH --error=slurm.%N.%j.err      # STDERR output file (optional)

# Directories
output_dir="./fastq_files"
aligned_dir="./aligned_reads"
qc_dir="./qc_reports"

# Create directories if they do not exist
mkdir -p $output_dir $aligned_dir $qc_dir

# Load necessary modules
module load FastQC
module load STAR
module load java

# Loop through each SRR number in the text file
while IFS= read -r srr_number; do
  echo "Processing $srr_number..."

  # Download FASTQ files
  sratoolkit.3.1.1-ubuntu64/bin/fasterq-dump $srr_number -O $output_dir

  # Run FastQC
  echo "Run FastQC"
  fastqc $output_dir/${srr_number}.fastq -o $qc_dir

  # Align reads using STAR
  echo "Align reads using STAR"
  STAR --runThreadN 6 \
       --runMode alignReads \
       --genomeDir genome/ \
       --readFilesIn $output_dir/${srr_number}.fastq \
       --outFileNamePrefix $aligned_dir/${srr_number}_ \
       --outSAMtype BAM SortedByCoordinate \
       --outSAMunmapped Within \
       --outSAMattributes Standard 

  # Remove initial FASTQ files
  echo "Remove initial fq file" 
  rm $output_dir/${srr_number}.fastq # not enough memory
  
  echo "Finish $srr_number... Go to the next SRR file"

done < homework3_srr.txt

echo "Processing complete."

counts <- read.table("/Users/uran/Downloads/count.out", sep="\t", header=T, row.names=1)

counts$X.projects.f_amitrofa_1.uran.HW3.bams.SRR6305400_Aligned.sortedByCoord.out.bam <- NULL

# Rename columns of counts data to match to meta_data names
for (col in names(counts)) {
  new_name <- gsub(".*SRR(\\d+)_.*", "\\1", col)
  new_name <- paste('SRR', new_name, sep='')
  counts[[new_name]] <- counts[[col]]
  counts[[col]] <- NULL
}

# Convert ENSG ids to gene names for further usage and analysis
mart <- useMart("ensembl", dataset = "hsapiens_gene_ensembl")
genes <- getBM(attributes = c("ensembl_gene_id", "external_gene_name"),
               filters = "ensembl_gene_id",
               values = rownames(counts),
               mart = mart)

rownames(counts) <- make.names(rownames(counts))
counts <- tibble::rownames_to_column(counts, var='ensembl_id')
counts <- merge(counts, genes, by.x = "ensembl_id", by.y = "ensembl_gene_id", all.x = F)

counts$external_gene_name <- make.unique(counts$external_gene_name)
counts <- tibble::column_to_rownames(counts, var = "external_gene_name")
counts$ensembl_id <- NULL

Deseq2

#colData is a data frame of demographic/phenotypic data
dds <- DESeqDataSetFromMatrix(countData = counts,
                              colData=meta_data,
                              design=~disease_status)

#Gene Filtering
dds<-dds[rowSums(counts(dds))>1,]
#Performs estimation of size factors,
#dispersion, and negative binomial GLM fitting

Limma

#From edgeR, Computes library size
dge <- DGEList(counts=counts, group=group[1:31])

#Gene Filtering
counts<-counts[which(rowSums(cpm(counts))>1),]
dge <- DGEList(counts=counts, group=group)
dge <- calcNormFactors(dge) #TMM normalization
design<-model.matrix(~group)
#voom transform to calculate weights to
#eliminate mean-variance relationship
v<-voom(dge, design)
#use usual limma pipelines
fit<-lmFit(v,design)
fit<-eBayes(fit)
# topTable(fit, coef=ncol(design), number=50)
datatable(topTable(fit, coef=ncol(design), number=50), options = list(pageLength=5))
# Get top differentially expressed genes
top_genes <- topTable(fit, coef=ncol(design), number=50)
top_genes_limma <- top_genes
degs <- rownames(top_genes)

# Extract log CPM for DEGs
log_cpm <- cpm(dge, log=TRUE)
mat <- log_cpm[degs, ]

# Normalize the matrix for heatmap visualization
mat <- t(scale(t(mat)))

# Create a data frame for annotation
df <- data.frame(disease_status=colData(sce_hivtb)$disease_status)

# Ensure levels match exactly
df$disease_status <- factor(df$disease_status, levels=c("TB-HIV", "HIV"))

# Create heatmap annotation
ha <- HeatmapAnnotation(df=df,
                        col=list(disease_status=c("TB-HIV"="Red", "HIV"="Blue")))

# Generate heatmap
Heatmap(mat, show_row_names=FALSE, show_column_names=FALSE, top_annotation=ha)
